<h2>Walking Tours (Haunted Walks)</h2>
<h3>What a Haunted Walk Is</h3>
<p>A haunted walk is a guided stroll through a city or neighborhood, stopping at sites with spooky reputations. The guide mixes local history with ghost lore and often uses theatrical elements to spook and entertain you.</p>
<p>You’ll get a feel for the place after sunset, hear stories you won’t find in guidebooks, and see the architecture that gives the tales their mood.</p>
<h3>What to Expect</h3>
<p>Expect about 60–90 minutes on your feet, a group of other tourists, and a guide who knows how to pace tension and humor. Some walks include brief interactive moments like calling out into the dark or using a handheld spirit box.</p>
<p>Don’t expect heavy equipment or deep investigative methodology — haunted walks are storytelling-led. If you want technical investigations, look for overnight hunts.</p>
<h3>Typical Duration &amp; Cost</h3>
<p>Most haunted walks are 1–2 hours and cost around $15–$40. Premium, small-group or private walks can cost more and sometimes include bonus locations.</p>
<h3>Who It’s Best For</h3>
<p>You, if you want historical context plus a spooky atmosphere without committing an entire night. Haunted walks are great for first-timers, families (check age policies), and travelers with limited time.</p>
<h3>Safety &amp; Accessibility</h3>
<p>Guides should provide meeting points with clear directions and be upfront about stairs, uneven cobblestones, or narrow passages. Ask about wheelchair access before booking; some routes aren’t wheelchair-friendly but operators often offer alternate routes or advisory notes.</p>
<h3>Tips &amp; What to Pack</h3>
<ul>
<li>Wear comfortable shoes and a jacket; nights get cold.</li>
<li>Bring a small flashlight but keep it discreet so you don’t break immersion.</li>
<li>If you want a photo, practice low-light phone settings; flash ruins the mood and other people’s experience.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Bus Tours</h2>
<h3>What a Bus Tour Involves</h3>
<p>Bus tours take the city-wide haunted narrative to the street level, often at night. You’ll pass multiple locations, sometimes stopping to hear a story or to briefly walk around a landmark.</p>
<p>These tours combine storytelling with the convenience of a seated ride, which is great if you prefer less walking but want a broad sweep of haunted spots.</p>
<h3>What to Expect</h3>
<p>Expect 1.5–3 hours with onboard narration and occasional live commentary. Some operators include recorded reenactments or multimedia displays. The group size is often larger than walking tours, so interaction can be limited.</p>
<h3>Typical Duration &amp; Cost</h3>
<p>Most bus tours run 1.5–3 hours and cost $20–$60. Luxury or themed buses (period-style or full reenactments) can raise the price.</p>
<h3>Who It’s Best For</h3>
<p>You, if you prefer a guided experience with minimal walking, or you’re traveling in a larger group and want a shared evening that’s easy to coordinate.</p>
<h3>Safety &amp; Accessibility</h3>
<p>Buses often have better disability access than walking routes; check for wheelchair lifts and reserved seating. Ask about age policies because some content and dramatic effects may be unsuitable for children.</p>
<h3>Tips &amp; What to Pack</h3>
<ul>
<li>Bring a light jacket; buses can be chilly.</li>
<li>If motion sickness is a concern, choose a seat near the front.</li>
<li>Keep your camera ready for exterior shots of lit landmarks.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Overnight Hunts (Paranormal Hunts)</h2>
<h3>What an Overnight Hunt Is</h3>
<p>An overnight hunt is a proper investigation: you stay at or near a haunted site, use investigator-grade equipment, and attempt to capture audio, EMF spikes, temperature anomalies, or visual phenomena.</p>
<p>This is where ghost tours turn investigative and the stakes — and the stories — get higher.</p>
<h3>What to Expect</h3>
<p>Expect long hours, periods of silence, and instruction from experienced investigators. Some hunts are very hands-on, letting you run meters, command the spirit box, or be part of stakeouts. Others focus on guided observation with professionals taking the lead.</p>
<p>You should be prepared for downtime, awkward silence, and a lot of waiting — that’s often when interesting things happen.</p>
<h3>Typical Duration &amp; Cost</h3>
<p>Most overnight hunts last from dusk to dawn and cost $80–$300+, depending on location, exclusivity, and equipment provided. Private hunts or sessions in very famous haunted sites can be pricier.</p>
<h3>Who It’s Best For</h3>
<p>You, if you have an appetite for a more serious paranormal investigation and you don’t mind losing sleep. If you like technical gadgets, night vision, and being part of an investigative team, an overnight hunt is ideal.</p>
<h3>Safety &amp; Accessibility</h3>
<p>Operators should provide clear safety briefings, emergency exits, and contact protocols. Old buildings can have hazards like loose flooring or limited lighting — ask operators about accessibility and whether they can accommodate mobility limitations.</p>
<h3>Tips &amp; What to Pack</h3>
<ul>
<li>Bring earplugs and a light sleeping pad; some sites have communal sleeping areas.</li>
<li>Pack snacks, water, and charged batteries for personal devices.</li>
<li>Respect the site and local rules: many overnight hunts take place in historically sensitive locations.</li>
</ul>
<h2>DIY Hunts (Independent Paranormal Investigations)</h2>
<h3>What a DIY Hunt Looks Like</h3>
<p>If you prefer to do things your way, you can organize a DIY hunt: book access, bring your gear, and form a small team. DIY hunts give you complete control over methods and timing.</p>
<p>You’ll manage logistics, safety, and the entire investigative flow. It’s more work but also more autonomy.</p>
<h3>What to Expect</h3>
<p>Expect planning: permissions, site rules, and equipment checks. If you DIY in historic or private places, you must secure written permission and follow any restrictions. Solo exploring buildings without permission is unsafe and illegal.</p>
<h3>Typical Duration &amp; Cost</h3>
<p>Cost varies widely — equipment rental can be inexpensive, but site fees or permits can add up. Duration is up to you, from a few hours to a full night.</p>
<h3>Who It’s Best For</h3>
<p>You, if you’re confident in logistics and want the freedom to investigate on your terms. DIY hunts suit experienced investigators and those with access to local knowledge.</p>
<h3>Safety &amp; Accessibility</h3>
<p>Safety is your responsibility. Always inform someone about your plans, check structural hazards, and have first-aid supplies. Accessibility depends entirely on the site and your ability to negotiate it.</p>
<h3>Tips &amp; What to Pack</h3>
<ul>
<li>Obtain written permission and verify insurance requirements.</li>
<li>Have a clear team leader and communication plan.</li>
<li>Use a mix of entry-level and some pro gear: digital recorders, infrared thermometers, and flashlights.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Evidence Capture: Tools, Techniques, and Responsible Interpretation</h2>
<h3>Core Equipment</h3>
<p>Your kit doesn’t need to be intimidating. A few reliable tools will get you started and make your reports usable.</p>
